==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Annoucement</span>==

''Welcome everyone to the ultimate amusement destination in the lands of labyrinth and wonders! After some extended renovations, we are pleased to announce our newest and biggest adventure yet! Everyone knows of our original location in Entertainland. But we knew it wasn't enough, we wanted more! We wanted to be bolder, bigger, and provide the ultimate thrilling experience for all wanderers alike!''

''After careful planning and building, we have done it! We are pleased to all of you, Coney Island! This park has everything everyone wants! From the most thrilling of rides, to the most delicious of foods, to the wackiest of shows, we have everything you have dreamed of! So what are you waiting for? Come on down and ride our rides, eat our foods, watch our shows, and have a wonderful and wacky day of fun here at Coney Island!''

==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Description</span>==

Coney Island is an Art-Deco style amusement park. It contains every known feature of amusement parks from the 1910s and 1920s. All of the buildings, stands, and rides have mostly Art-Deco looks and theming. There are other architecture styles including Beaux-Arts and Art Nouveau alongside some other architecture styles that existed before or during the 1920s. 
{{Blurimage|file=Coney Island Nighttime.jpg|caption=Coney Island at night.|}}
The rides at Coney Island are identical to rides that existed before or during the 1920s in the frontrooms, regardless if they no longer exist or still exist. The shops all have items from that existed during the 1920s that include clothing, food and drinks, etc. The shows all use technology made during the 1920s, and will broadcast movies from that time. There are also two live shows that Coney Island will do, one live show during the day, and one at nightime. Both take place in the same showground arena.

===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Rides</span>===
{{Blurimage|file=Coney Island.jpg|caption=The first ever recorded image of Level 320.|}}

Coney Island contains rides from the 1900s through to the 1930s. Most of them are safe to ride, with a few exceptions. Rides which have theming around eyes are for entities only and if one tries to ride it, they will be harassed by [[Glowfolk]] who will not like that one tried to ride a ride exclusively to them. 

If one spots a red dot on a ride, it is a trap ride. If one gets on it, they will be permanently stuck riding it forever until they die. It is very hard to spot red dot rides, as the dots are usually on a part of the ride that wanderers overlook. 

Rides with a glitching effect are safe to ride by themselves, but the after-effects are mixed. When one exits the ride, they themselves are glitching. A wanderer who has a glitching effect are harder to spot by hostile entities, and the pain they receive is minimal and can withstand far more attacks from hostile entities more than the average wanderer. The cost however is that they will be partially blinded, and they will require more nutritional intake. They will go thirsty and hungry faster than the average wanderer. The effect will last 48 hours.



===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>The Shops</span>===

The shops at Coney Island are mostly dedicated to a single genre of stuff, mainly clothing and food/drink shops. All of the shop's items and materials they are made of regardless of object are exactly the same as their frontroom counterparts. There are no prices toward these items. Instead, there is a limit per store about how many you can take. The glowfolk behind a counter at a food/drink store takes more than three drinks or foods, two pieces of clothing from the clothing store, five pieces of candy from a candy store, etc. When a certain item is out, the glowfolk behind the counter will go to the back of the store and get more of that item. They never run out of any item.
{{Blurimage|file=Candy Shop.jpg|caption=A Candy Shop|}}
If one exceeds that limit, the glowfolk behind the counter will refuse that person to leave the store. If one does attempt to leave the store while exceeding the maximum limit, the glowfolk will get aggressive and force that person to hand all of their items back to them and will order them to leave that particular store.

One item that is common across all stores and is free to take without consequence is [[Object 1|Almond Water]]. The glowfolk behind every counter will allow one to take as many as they want. The green variant of the water however can only be found in drink shops, but the blue variant can be found at every shop.

===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>The Shows</span>===

Coney Island has movie theaters rarely pop up at Coney Island but when it does it will have two movies playing in two separate screening rooms. The movies can vary, but every film made after 1919 and before 1929 can be played, including lost films. Most of the films will be silent, but some will have sound.

Outside of the movie theaters, Coney Island has two live performance shows. One will be performed during the day, the other at night. They are preformed a Open-Air Theater in the center of Coney Island, which also acts as the exact center of the level. 

The Daytime show begins at 12 in the afternoon exactly, where it starts off with a live band performance. After which the park will showcase animals, even some that are extinct in the frontrooms. All of the animals showcased will perform tricks for the people attending. After the showcase, a massive magic show will happen with various tricks being preformed. The live band lasts 30 minutes, the animal showcase also lasts around 30 minutes, and the magic show lasts for one hour.

The Nighttime show starts at midnight. It starts off with a massive light show where lights will perform live music and illuminate a short story. After the light show, there will be a live talent show where various glowfolks will display unusual talents ranging from unusual body features to live performances. The show will end with a stunt show, ranging from human cannonballs, car stunts, etc. The light show lasts 15 minutes, the talent show lasts one hour, and the stunt show lasts 45 minutes.  

===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Wonderous Amusement Syndrome</span>===

The Wonderous Amusement Syndrome (W.A.S) for short, is a slow progressive syndrome that starts as soon as a wanderer either rides their first ride, eats their first bit of candy from the level, or wear a piece of clothing from the level. It is a collection of symptoms that one by one, slowly make the wanderer become permanently stuck in Coney Island and will never make them want to leave nor will they be able to exit the level.

The W.A.S will not start progressing for the wanderer until 3 hours have passed from one of the three triggers. The first symptom is that they will be happy more than they usually are, though this can be harder to detect in wanderers who are always more in a positive mood. But around after 5 hours have passed, they will smile to the point it is noticeable to all wanderers.
Around 9 hours into getting the Syndrome, the second symptom will appear. The wanderer will want to ride more rides than usual, even on rides that wanderer wanted to avoid. This is the same case for the shows and shops, particularly candy ones if the candy piece was the trigger.

The third symptom that appears around 12 hours in, is that their entire faces will turn pale. 13 hours in, their entire body will have a pale color. It is also at this point they will start talking to glowfolk more often. The fourth symptom that triggers 14 hours in is that they will slowly forget everything of their past. They will forget everything except their name and age. They will forget everything else 30 minutes after. The fifth and final symptom of W.A.P is that they will be unable to exit the level at all 16 hours after the initial trigger of the virus.


==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Entities</span>==



===Glowfolk===

[[Glowfolk]] are everywhere at Coney Island. They double as both visitors to the amusement park and workers there. They are all generally pretty friendly and won't become hostile unless provoked. They are all dressed in 1920s-style clothing and speak using terms from that time. Some of them are quite social and will try to talk to wanderers. It is encouraged to do so as it can help one's mental state and improve their understanding of the level.

'''The Fun Man''' is aware of their behaviours, their life cycle, what they are made out of, and other necessary and important details about them. In knowing all of it, he has developed a plan for every Glowfolk in Coney Island. This plan involves every step of their lives and how they will live it.
{{Blurimage|file=LuminousFiction Glowfolk.webp|caption=Portrait of a Glowfolk wearing Art Deco attire.|}}
When the spark of a glowfolk first appears, '''The Fun Man''' and other Glowfolk assisting him will contain those sparks into specially designed to both block their radiation properties and let them learn how both guests and employees act. '''The Fun Man''' and his assistants will give the growing sparks a specially made "calming fuel" that both lets them grow and calmly learn behaviours of those at Coney Island. Their lanterns will either be hanged on random poles, on walls, or in other places in the park that allow them to see both other glowfolk and wanderers.

After a while, when those sparks eventually mature and transform into a flame, they are separated from the park itself into a specially developed area made by the '''The Fun Man'''. This area hosts a school for the flames to learn how to act properly with those at Coney Island and other important and vital lessons. It also hosts temporary apartments for the flames to stay at until they both become a Glowfolk (Inferno) and graduate from the school. They are given the calming fuel for them both to grow and control their tempers.

When they finally mature and transform into their final stage, they will be given a role as either an employee or a visitor by '''The Fun Man'''. They will also be given proper accommodations outside of the park itself, in an unknown level that '''The Fun Man''' refuses to disclose for safety reasons. It is also at this stage they switch to a more advanced calming fuel.  This version of the calming fuel is designed to drop their radiation levels to almost nonexistent to safely interact with wanderers. They are given this more advanced calming fuel on a weekly basis.

===The Fun Man===

The Fun Man is a nickname for a mysterious entity that appears at Coney Island. He will appear when one enters the level and introduce them to the level. He will not speak of the ride types or shop rules but will speak of one exit if one asks. He will also let you know 15 minutes before every live-performance show that it will start soon and will guide one to the Open-Air Theater. If one also asks for the nearest shop or specific type of shop, he will gladly help and also guide the wanderer to it.
{{Blurimage|file=The Fun Man.png||caption=Artist's conception of The Fun Man.|}}
He has a mostly normal human body, but in the place of a head is instead a floating piece of dice. All sides of the floating head dice have question marks on them. When asked of it, he says he doesn't know how it got there. All he will say is that he considers it a neat part of himself and likes it.

He will also act of the host of both the daytime and nighttime shows, announcing every little bit. From announcing the winner of the talent show to commenting on various animals showcases, he will act very excited at every little bit. He is also present on banners everywhere in the level advertising various things from clothes to candy.

===Jeremiah===

Jeremiah is a little ghost, who has a white hue covering his entire body. He mostly appears in the candy shop looking at treats he can eat. Despite being a ghost, he can eat treats and wear clothes from the various shops in the level. He will also rarely ride the rides at Coney Island and see the shows. His origins however are unclear, as when asking The Fun Man about Jeremiah, he says that he does not come from the level originally and that he is from another place entirely. 
{{Blurimage|file=Jeremy.png||caption=Photo of Jeremiah in a candy shop.|}}
He is a very friendly entity who likes to chat with everyone in the level, ranging from wanderers, glowfolk, to even both The Fun Man and the string of Mirth himself. He will mostly want to talk about the various offerings of Coney Island, mainly the candy it offers. He will however sit down and listen to the wanderers if they wish to talk to him about various things the wanderer has seen, done, etc. When the wanderer is done, Jeremiah will do the best he can to offer advice, to compliment the wanderer, etc. If he does not understand what the wanderer is talking about, he will just nod along. Overall, talking with Jeremiah will improve one's mental state considerably. 

{{Collapse|num=2|initial='' I still don't understand...''|final='''> "I'll do my best...master."|body=
<br>"...I still don't know why he is [[Level 320|here]]. I know he is your son and all, but not take him with you? I still don't understand why you didn't take him to that paradise of yours. Though I do understand the delicate balance that place needs to have, I am sure one child would not change anything. ...But I am not one to question your decision master. After all, you created me solely the purpose of watching over this land...and your child. The String of Mirth has also been helpful in entertaining your child, though I am still not sure what you think of...him being here. Regardless, I hope everything is going well my master. I hope your [[Level 665|paradise]] is doing well, and to hope one day...see you again. - The Fun Man.

P.S - I know you seek her, but she has yet to even enter this realm we preside in. But if she is like anything you have said...she will find us eventually. I just hope it will not be too late by the time she finds us. ...You two will reunite, I know it. I have yet to meet her in person...but I hope I do. If she is as brave as you are master, she will find us.}}


==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Groups and Organizations</span>==

The Fun Man makes sure that no permanent bases are installed at Coney Island. He will allow every group to have temporary bases, but only for 48 hours maximum and only once per month. 

There is however one exception made to a certain member of a certain group. The String of Mirth from [[The Strings]] has been allowed to permanently live on this level if he chooses to. The Fun Man found him amusing, and therefore saw his potential to entertain wanderers and glowfolks alike. So long as he makes the glowfolks and wanderers laugh, he can live in this level forever. 

He can also take whatever items he wants from any stores with no limits, no matter the item. He is also provided an apartment on the second floor of a candy shop across from the Open-theater, where he is also provided a VIP seat alongside The Fun Man. 


==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Entrances and Exits</span>==

===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Entrances</span>===

In [[Level 711]], if one finds a Fun Man plush lying a shelf of candy products and picks it up, they must say that they want to find joy. Once they say it they will be transported here. 

In [[Level 64]], if one finds a ticket for Coney Island and picks it up, they will be brought here.  

In [[Level 955]], if one finds a random Art-Deco hat and wears it, they will be brought here.

===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #FFF301;>Exits</span>=== 

There is a very rare chance that one can find a golden ticket on the ground. Give to the Fun Man and he will bring you to [[Level 513]].

If one finds a red door in any of the shops and goes through it, they will end up in either [[Level 507]] or [[Level 321]].

If one asks the Fun Man for a way out, he will lead them to a hole. He will tell you to jump in. Once one jumps in the hole, they will end up in [[Level 215]].


